tspan.tspan: BUTTON AND SWITCH TEMPLATES
Here are some predefined button & label combinations to
speed up the panel making process. The template will also
have links to commonly used switches and other
components
that fit these holes and button cap designs.
Many button types are constructed from a 3D printed switch
body, and a fitting button cap with the engraved text label,
cut
out of 0.8mm engraving sheet. The cap is simply
superglued on
the top of the 3D printed button.
NOTE
: These things are on several layers - bottom acrylic,
top
acrylic (panel sheets) and also the button cap engraving
layer. DUPLICATING (Ctrl-D)
will keep it this way, but if you
copy & paste or
group them,
they end up in the same layer,
which is not what you want for easy separation of layers
when cutting the panel.
TEXT AND FONTS
This template uses
Bahnschrift
font which is
included in
Windows 10.
This works well for
cockpit panels because it
is very clear
and
readable, has good
legibility also when
engraved, and it
resembles closely the
fonts that are being used
in cockpits.
Airbus uses a very similar
font, but some Boeing
panels
(though not all)
use
Futura
which is not
freely available, so
sadly
we cannot include it in
this template.

tspan.tspan: Panel templates for flight simulator projects
These panel templates lets you quickly design consistent simulated aircraft cockpit
panels using a CO2 laser cutter or CNC router and acrylic sheets. Combined with
electronic circuit board designs it is possible to build affordable flight simulator add-on-
panels for both entertainment and training purposes. The designs utilize MobiFlight, free
and open source software that utilizes common Arduino boards and lets you connect
functional buttons, leds and switches to flight simulator software.
These panels use the DZUS mounting rail spacing for holes and panel sizes, but contain
M4 sized holes for screws for practical reasons.
These panels consist of two layers:
bottom clear acrylic sheet, and top white acrylic sheet.
There is also a paint mask template for the lower layer (since the edges and mounting
hole areas need to be painted, but the center needs to be transparent so that the
backlighting can shine through. Those blue lines frame the inner clear area, thus you can
cover the lower panel completely with painters tape, vector cut the tape and remove the
center area.
If you use K40 Whisperer to do the laser cutting, you can export a particular layer for
cutting by hiding all other layers before saving; K40 Whisperer only loads the visible layer.
How to make even larger panels?
These are the most common sizes, for larger panels you need to pick an existing panel
with matching style and resize it. The width of the panels are the standard 5.75" (5.365"
hole to hole horizontally) and heights are incrementally growing within the hole pattern,
When you resize, it helps to open Edit > Preferences and set Behavior > Steps: "Arrow keys
move by" to 0,3750 inches, that is the spacing of the Dzus rail holes.
Then you need to select each part of the panel separately, use the "node edit" tool and
"rubber band select" nodes on the other end and use cursor keys to move all those nodes
to the final size you want. Pay close attention that your selection "splits" the panel in a
straight edge, so you don't deform the curved parts. Do this to the back plate, the backlight
plate (the smoothly curved one) and finally the mounting holes.
IF YOU DON'T LIKE INSTRUCTIONS, READ THIS
ONE:
Open this file in INKSCAPE (www.inkscape.org). If you use Illustrator or something
else, it tends to do some weird clipping stuff and things will just be messed up. This is a
template made specifically for laser cutting, so stay away from any other tool. Inkscape is
open source and works for Linux, Windows and Mac. It's not worth it trying to edit this with
something else since we want this to be usable for everyone, regardless of whether they
can afford expensive software.
TWO: Everything is organized in LAYERS
press Ctrl-Shift-L) to make it easy to
separate things later when cutting the panel. This is why things are red and black, and
this is why there are those varying sized circles and rectangles around everything. Those
are various sized holes for each layer of the panel. When you copy the switch templates,
do NOT cut and paste
, as this drops them all in the selected layer. Instead do Edit ->
Duplicate (Ctrl-D) and move the new copy to your panel with cursor keys or using the
mouse. It often helps to move it first to a clear area with the arrow keys so you can select
easier. Also
do NOT group things
. It would be convenient, but groups also move things
into one layer.
